  <span id="freeText8092248462637664933" style="display:none">When you think of a neuroscientist you probably think of someone cold, clinical and unmoved by emotions, but Oliver Sacks writes with so much heart. The writing itself is so elegant you hardly realize you're reading about something as complex as the human brain. <br /><br />What we have here are vignettes of various disorders relating to hearing, speech, movement and memory - all of them tied to music in one way or another. <br /><br />While every page of this book was gripping, the chapter on 'Music and Identity' was so moving. It speaks to the depths to which music can move us, affect us and ultimately transform us. It truly sits at the very bedrock of one's being in some sense. <br /><br />Here is one passage that I truly think is unforgettable:<br /><br /><i>I was passionately fond of my mother’s sister, my Auntie Len; I often felt she had saved my sanity, if not my life, when I was sent away from home as a child, evacuated from London during the war. Her death left a sudden huge hole in my life, but, for some reason, I had difficulty mourning. I went about my work, my daily life, functioning in a mechanical way, but inside I was in a state of anhedonia, numbly unresponsive to all pleasure—and, equally, sadness. One evening I went to a concert, hoping against hope that the music might revive me, but it did not work; the whole concert bored me—until the last piece was played. It was a piece I had never heard before, by a composer I had never heard of, The Lamentations of Jeremiah by Jan Dismus Zelenka (an obscure Czech contemporary of Bach’s, I later learned). Suddenly, as I listened, I found my eyes wet with tears. My emotions, frozen for weeks, were flowing once again. Zelenka’s Lamentations had broken the dam, letting feeling flow where it had been obstructed, immobilized inside me.</i><br /><br />Well, I did mention that he writes very elegantly, didn't I?<br /><br />Music cannot represent anything, it has no symbolic value whatsoever and yet it touches the very core of our being, reaching to places within us that we didn't know existed. Come think of it, it's so abstract and so very real at the same time. Not to mention it fills you with so much awe and wonder that even for an agnostic like me, it has a touch of what can only be called divine.</span>
