  <span id="freeText15633745906929125635" style="display:none">Music has been part of my life for most of it. . . .only in the last few has it been falling to a lower tier in my attentions and focus - and I couldn't tell you why. So I am much more aware of the spaces where it is when it pops in these days. . . .because mostly it isn't in my life. I don't have music on, I'm not working on my instruments, nor am I involved in vocal work. I blame it on age, on rough performance and all that combines to avoidance and disappointment rather than joy. All that makes me quite confused.<br /><br />Then I read this book. It was mostly over my head - most of Oliver's work is over my head - but the bits I got, I got straight into my heart. I'm at a spot in my life where I begin to lose words - it's totally alarming as I have always been a word girl - but you give me a tune - I can remember anything. The therapies he discusses, I can see how they would work and how patients would thrive as long as that music plays.<br /><br />Very deep and very interesting - I only got 3 stars in because of my lack of knowledge - anyone who is interested in music, enjoys it, and feels it throughout their body beyond just their ears would find this a good read. Music, brains and bodies. . . as if we, ourselves, are instruments in this wide world and space.</span>
